  <h2 id="why-targeted">Why Diaspora Businesses Are Targeted</h2>

  <p>Diaspora-owned businesses in Ghana have a structural vulnerability that locally owned businesses do not: the owner is absent. This single fact changes the fraud calculus for every person who interacts with the business.</p>

  <p>A local business owner in Accra can walk into the shop unannounced, count the stock, check the cash drawer, observe staff behaviour, and verify supplier deliveries in person. A diaspora founder in London, Toronto, or New York cannot do any of these things. They rely on reports, and reports can be fabricated.</p>

  <p>GhanaWorld's failure pattern FP-001 (Delegation before control systems) is classified as GHANA-AMPLIFIED because formal audit and accountability norms in Ghana's SME operating environment are weaker than in higher-income markets. Detection of financial leakage is slower. Controls installed after a loss rarely recover what was stolen.</p>

  <p>FP-012 (Fraud prevention added after first loss) confirms the pattern: the opacity of informal cash-handling norms in Ghana's SME environment means that the absence of controls is quickly exploited. Recovery of stolen cash or inventory through legal channels is slow and expensive.</p>

  <div class="risk-box">
    <h4>The Core Problem</h4>
    <p>Fraud risk rises when owner absence meets weak controls (DL-006). This is not about Ghana being uniquely dishonest. It is about the structural incentive created when money flows through a business that nobody is verifying. The same pattern exists everywhere in the world where absentee ownership meets absent oversight. Ghana's weaker institutional enforcement of contracts and slower legal recovery makes the consequences worse.</p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="seven-fraud-types">The Seven Fraud Types That Hit Diaspora Founders</h2>

  <p>Based on 40 cycles of GhanaWorld analysis, these are the specific fraud categories that damage diaspora-owned businesses in Ghana. They are listed in order of frequency, not severity.</p>

  <h3>1. Cash Skimming</h3>
  <p>Staff collects revenue and reports a lower figure. In a cash-heavy business (retail, food service, hospitality), the daily leakage can reach 10 to 20 percent of revenue without detection if no reconciliation system exists. The owner sees the reported numbers and believes the business is underperforming when it is actually being stolen from.</p>

  <h3>2. Ghost Workers</h3>
  <p>The local manager adds fictional employees to the payroll and collects their salaries. In a business with 10 to 20 staff, one or two ghost workers may not trigger suspicion, especially if the diaspora owner has never met all staff members in person. Monthly cost: GHS 2,000 to 5,000 per ghost worker at typical SME salary levels.</p>

  <h3>3. Supplier Collusion</h3>
  <p>The manager selects suppliers who charge inflated prices and shares the markup. This is difficult to detect remotely because the owner does not know local market prices for materials, ingredients, or services. The invoices look legitimate. The quantities look reasonable. But the per-unit costs are 15 to 40 percent above market rate.</p>

  <h3>4. Inventory Diversion</h3>
  <p>Stock is removed from the business and sold separately. Common in retail, wholesale, and any business that holds physical inventory. Without regular inventory counts verified against purchase records and sales data, the loss is invisible until stock levels become obviously low.</p>

  <h3>5. Construction and Renovation Fraud</h3>
  <p>Contractor quotes inflated costs, uses cheaper materials than specified, and pockets the difference. This is particularly dangerous for diaspora founders who are funding construction from abroad. Without an independent site inspector, the owner receives photos of progress that may not reflect reality. Cement grade, rebar gauge, plumbing quality, and electrical standards are impossible to verify from a photograph.</p>

  <h3>6. Land Title Fraud</h3>
  <p>Detailed in the section below. Ghana's land tenure system creates specific vulnerabilities that do not exist in markets with consolidated land registries.</p>

  <h3>7. Procurement Padding</h3>
  <p>The manager inflates quantities on purchase orders. The business orders 50 bags of cement; 40 arrive at the site; 10 are diverted. The receipt shows 50. Without an independent receiving system, the 10-bag discrepancy disappears.</p>

