  <h2 id="bank-visibility">Bank Visibility: Your Remote Eyes</h2>

  <p>The diaspora founder should have view-only access to all business bank accounts. This is non-negotiable.</p>

  <p>GhanaWorld diaspora lesson DL-020 (the SOE accountability lesson) makes the structural case: institutions with external accountability and verifiable revenue survive better than those without. Bank visibility is the diaspora founder's primary external accountability mechanism.</p>

  <p>What bank visibility means in practice:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Internet banking access.</strong> Most Ghanaian commercial banks (GCB, Ecobank, Stanbic, Absa, Fidelity) offer internet banking with view-only access profiles. Set this up before operations begin, not after something goes wrong.</li>
    <li><strong>Daily balance checks.</strong> Spend 2 minutes each morning checking the account balance and recent transactions. This is the simplest, most effective monitoring activity a diaspora founder can perform.</li>
    <li><strong>Deposit verification.</strong> Compare daily bank deposits against the daily cash reconciliation sheet. If the reconciliation says GHS 8,000 was deposited and the bank shows GHS 6,500, you have a problem that is exactly GHS 1,500 in size.</li>
    <li><strong>Withdrawal alerts.</strong> Set up SMS or email alerts for all withdrawals above a threshold. You should know about every significant cash movement in real time, not at the end of the month.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Bank visibility does not require the owner to manage the account day-to-day. The local manager handles operations. But the owner sees everything. This asymmetry of information, where the manager knows the owner is watching, changes behaviour more effectively than any employment contract or trust-based appeal.</p>

  <h2 id="supplier-controls">Supplier Approval Controls</h2>

  <p>Supplier collusion is one of the hardest fraud types to detect because the invoices look legitimate. The quantities are reasonable. The prices are plausible to someone who does not know the local market. The only defence is a structured supplier approval system.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Approved supplier list.</strong> Maintain a list of approved suppliers for each category (raw materials, packaging, maintenance, office supplies). The list is established during the system-building phase when the owner is present and can verify prices in person.</li>
    <li><strong>Price benchmarking.</strong> For each approved supplier, record the agreed price for standard items. Any purchase above the agreed price by more than 10 percent requires owner approval before payment.</li>
    <li><strong>Three-way matching.</strong> Every payment requires three documents to match: the purchase order (what was ordered), the delivery note (what was received), and the invoice (what is being charged). Discrepancies between any two trigger a hold on payment.</li>
    <li><strong>Rotation requirement.</strong> For any recurring purchase above GHS 5,000 per month, obtain quotes from at least two suppliers quarterly. This prevents a single supplier relationship from becoming an entrenched collusion channel.</li>
    <li><strong>Owner approval threshold.</strong> Any single purchase above a set threshold (adjust for your business; GHS 2,000 to 5,000 is typical for SMEs) requires owner approval via WhatsApp or email before the order is placed. Not after.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="system-building">The 90-Day System-Building Window</h2>

  <p>GhanaWorld diaspora lesson DL-009 states that founder presence is most valuable during the system-building phase: hiring, supplier screening, control installation, and quality standard setting.</p>

  <p>DL-001 reinforces this: no business is remote-viable from Day 1. Even businesses that may later become remotely manageable require founder presence to install systems, select managers, and establish operating discipline.</p>

  <p>The first 90 days of operations are when you install the systems described in this guide. This is not a period you can delegate. This is the period during which you physically sit in the business, count cash, meet suppliers, interview staff, test the reporting systems, and verify that every control works in practice, not just in your business plan.</p>

  <p>What the 90-day system-building window looks like:</p>

  <div class="data-box">
    <h4>90-Day System-Building Timeline</h4>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Period</th><th>Focus</th><th>Deliverable</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Days 1 to 14</td><td>Bank accounts, mobile money, POS setup</td><td>All financial infrastructure operational with owner visibility</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Days 15 to 30</td><td>Hiring, contracts, payroll system</td><td>All staff on payroll with verified identities and bank accounts</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Days 31 to 45</td><td>Supplier identification and price benchmarking</td><td>Approved supplier list with agreed prices documented</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Days 46 to 60</td><td>Daily reconciliation training and testing</td><td>Manager produces accurate daily reconciliation for 14 consecutive days</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Days 61 to 75</td><td>Inventory system and weekly count protocol</td><td>First three weekly inventory counts completed and reconciled</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Days 76 to 90</td><td>Remote monitoring test</td><td>Owner receives and verifies daily reports for 14 days while physically present but not intervening</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p>The last 14 days are critical. You are physically in Ghana, but you simulate being remote. You do not walk into the shop. You do not check the cash drawer. You rely solely on the reports, the bank account, and the mobile money statements. If discrepancies appear during this test period, you fix the system before you leave. If the reports are accurate for 14 consecutive days, you have evidence (not hope) that the system works.</p>

  <div class="risk-box">
    <h4>What Happens If You Skip the 90-Day Window</h4>
    <p>If you send capital to Ghana, hire a manager (family or otherwise), and attempt to manage remotely from Day 1, the following sequence is the most probable outcome based on GhanaWorld's failure pattern data:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Months 1 to 3: Reports arrive. Numbers look plausible. You believe the business is growing slowly but steadily.</li>
      <li>Months 4 to 6: Cash requests increase. The manager explains rising costs, difficult customers, or a slow season. You send more working capital.</li>
      <li>Months 7 to 12: You visit Ghana. The inventory is lower than reported. The cash does not reconcile. Staff you have never met cannot explain discrepancies. The bank balance is lower than it should be.</li>
      <li>Month 12 and beyond: You face a choice between injecting more capital (with the same absent controls) or writing off your investment.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>This sequence is not speculation. It is the documented pattern from FP-001, FP-012, and DL-006.</p>
  </div>

